    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p>Previously named <i>Dosinia lupinus orbigny</i> and considered to be a subspecies of the European <i>D. lupinus</i>, but now recognized as being a distinct species. Also previously named <i>Artemis orbignyi</i>.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1045",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell very heavy, almost perfectly circular apart from a dorsal depression just behind the hinge. Externally surface smooth except for finely-sculptured concentric growth lines. Colour uniform white to cream.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1046",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 53 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1047",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> From Senegal down Africa’s west coast to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Found all along the west and south coasts of southern African to about East London.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1048",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Burrows in clean sand and gravel sediments from low water to about 160 m depth. Popularly collected for human consumption in Angola, where it is known as 'ameijoinha'.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1049",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves feed by pumping water in via an inhalant siphon, filtering our fine particles though the enlarged gills and then ejecting the filtered water though an exhalent siphon.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1050",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves is a broadcast spawner. Details of reproductive cycle in this species have not been investigated.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1051",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Adults unlikely to be confused with other regional species due to the almost perfectly round, heavy and smooth shells. The Lesser heart clam<i> D. hepatica</i> is similar in shape, but much smaller (25 mm) and found only in estuaries from Gqeberha eastwards.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1052",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 158).<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 193).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1053",
